Final arithmetic
- Technology Adoption: 17
- Innovation Leadership: 16
- Measurable Impact: 13
- Future Strategy: 12
- Industry Position: 7
- Total = 17 + 16 + 13 + 12 + 7 = 65 / 100

Overall assessment
Allstate demonstrates a solid and credible sustainable-technology posture for a major insurer: explicit net-zero targets (2030 for scope 1/2 and relevant value chain), measurable investments ($2.9B climate-related portfolio, new commitments), operational actions (fleet hybridization progress, real-estate energy strategy, procurement/supplier engagement), and an active venture/investment approach to back climate tech. However, most technology adoption has been through procurement, financing, hybrid fleet conversion and corporate programs (RECs/offsets and investments) rather than large in-house, breakthrough technology deployments or proprietary R&D. Some key commitments (financed emissions targets, full Scope 3 targets) were scheduled for announcement by end of 2025 and remain important totrack. Overall, Allstate sits in the upper-middle tier among insurers on sustainable-technology adoption and leadership in the 2022–2025 window — active, well-governed, and investing, but not yet setting the clear technological pace across the sector.

